ly does. The syntax for JSON with interpolated strings is important here. When I use placeholders like `$name`, I need to ensure they're quoted correctly in the JSON format. I also wonder about defining custom encoders. For instance, creating a case class like Meter and providing an implicit Encoder could work well. I need to verify how this fits together with the KeyEncoder for producing JSON fields correctly.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering field key interpolation**\\n\\nI'm thinking there might be a potential conflict with field key interpolation when I consider it as an Any type. I'm particularly focusing on how the KeyEncoder interacts with a custom type like Meter. It’s crucial to ensure that the interpolation works smoothly and doesn’t produce unexpected errors. I need to delve into how these types interact within the Scala framework to avoid any issues with encoding or keys in JSON representation.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_SIJpDRzQqpN2RLCyfMjewKgP|fc_00b566ff89fec67e016a2a728bdaa481979d50a182f0060155", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "javap -classpath tests/src/io.circe/circe-literal_3/0.14.15/build/jacoco/effective/circe_literal_3_0_14_15_jar:$(find ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/io.circe/circe-core_3/0.14.15 -name '*.jar' -print | head -1) io.circe.Json 2>/dev/null | head -100"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2015, "output": 1297, "cacheRead": 20992, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 24304, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1781166696843, "responseId": "resp_00b566ff89fec67e016a2a726976508197b462534a540afda0"}}
